<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How much does wine cooler repair cost in Los Angeles?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Our diagnostic fee is $89, applied toward the repair once you approve the work. Most wine cooler repairs run between $120 and $320. A thermostat, door seal, or fan motor replacement is toward the lower end. Compressor work or control board replacement on premium units like EuroCave, Sub-Zero, or Liebherr runs higher — we provide a written estimate before any work begins."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "My wine cooler isn't cooling — is it the compressor or something else?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "It depends on the type of unit. On a thermoelectric wine cooler, 'not cooling' is almost never a compressor problem — these units use a Peltier module, not a compressor, and they have an important limitation: they can only cool about 20°F below the ambient room temperature. If your unit is in a warm room or unconditioned space, it may simply be unable to reach wine storage temperature regardless of whether anything is broken. On a compressor-based unit, not cooling points to the compressor, condenser fan, thermostat, or refrigerant. We diagnose the actual cause before recommending parts."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the difference between thermoelectric and compressor wine coolers?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Thermoelectric coolers use a Peltier module — no moving parts, no vibration, very quiet. They're excellent for collections where vibration is a concern. Their limitation: they can only cool about 20°F below ambient temperature, so they struggle in warm rooms and can't function properly in unconditioned spaces. Compressor coolers work like a small refrigerator — they can maintain wine storage temperature regardless of room temperature, but produce some vibration. For serious collections in LA, where ambient temperatures can be high, compressor units are usually more reliable."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "My wine cooler has zones that are cooling differently — what's wrong?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Uneven cooling across zones in a dual or multi-zone unit usually points to a failed zone fan motor — each zone has its own fan that circulates cooled air. A thermostat or temperature sensor that's drifted in one zone, or a damaged door seal allowing warm air to enter a specific section, can also cause temperature variation between zones. We test each zone independently before recommending parts."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does vibration from a wine cooler actually affect wine?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes, over time — particularly for aged wines with sediment. Vibration agitates sediment, keeps it in suspension rather than allowing it to settle, and can disrupt the slow chemical processes involved in wine aging. A wine cooler that's suddenly become loud and vibrating — often from a failing compressor or a loose fan — is worth repairing promptly for a collection you're aging. Thermoelectric units are preferable for sediment-sensitive bottles precisely because they have no moving compressor parts."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do you repair EuroCave, Liebherr, and other European wine cooler brands?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. EuroCave and Liebherr are the two European wine cooler brands we see most often in LA's serious collector market. Parts for these units sometimes require ordering from specialized distributors — we're upfront about lead times when that applies. Sub-Zero, U-Line, and Vinotemp we stock parts for more readily."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What does the 90-day warranty cover on wine cooler repairs?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Every wine cooler repair we complete carries a 90-day warranty on both parts and labor. If the same issue returns within that window, we come back at no charge. That's in writing before we leave."
      }
    }
  ]
}
</script>

