<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">06 — Recent Repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians actually fixed recently</h2>

    <div class="repairs-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Malibu · EuroCave Inspiration L</div>
        <h3>"Temperature keeps rising — started gradually, now it's 68°F in there"</h3>
        <p>Condenser fan motor failure on a EuroCave Inspiration L — a 200-bottle compressor unit. The condenser fan cools the compressor during operation; when it fails, the compressor overheats and cuts off on its thermal limiter. The unit would run briefly, hit temperature limit, shut off, cool down, restart — and gradually lose ground against the ambient temperature.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Sourced OEM EuroCave condenser fan motor (2-day lead time from European distributor). Replaced fan, verified compressor thermal limiter had reset correctly, ran 4-hour temperature test confirming stable 55°F throughout the unit. Customer had moved the most valuable bottles to the main fridge — we confirmed those could go back in once temperature stabilized.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Beverly Hills · Sub-Zero 424 Wine Storage</div>
        <h3>"Lower zone running cold, upper zone not cooling at all"</h3>
        <p>Dual-zone Sub-Zero 424 with the upper zone fan motor failed. The lower zone — with its own independent refrigeration circuit — was running correctly. The upper zone, which relies on its own fan to circulate cooled air from the evaporator, had stopped completely. Classic dual-zone failure where one zone's fan goes while the other remains operational.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced upper zone evaporator fan motor with OEM Sub-Zero part. Verified both zones achieving independent set temperatures within 45 minutes of repair. Also cleaned condenser coils — significant dust accumulation had been making the compressor work harder than necessary.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Silver Lake · Vinotemp VT-28TEDS Thermoelectric</div>
        <h3>"Not cooling at all — stopped working last week"</h3>
        <p>Before diagnosing the unit, we measured the ambient temperature in the customer's kitchen: 81°F. A thermoelectric unit rated to cool 20°F below ambient physically cannot reach 55°F wine storage temperature in that environment — even when working correctly. The unit wasn't broken; it was underpowered for the installation. The Peltier module was also drawing low current, suggesting it was beginning to fail.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Explained the thermoelectric limitation — in an LA kitchen in summer, this unit class cannot reliably maintain wine storage temperature. Replaced the Peltier module as it was failing anyway, but recommended upgrading to a compressor unit for this location. Customer appreciated the honest assessment rather than a repair that wouldn't solve the underlying problem.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">West Hollywood · U-Line 2275ZWCS</div>
        <h3>"Loud humming and vibrating more than before — have aged Burgundy in there"</h3>
        <p>Loose compressor mounting hardware — the compressor itself was functioning correctly but the rubber isolation mounts had deteriorated, transferring compressor vibration directly to the cabinet. For ordinary food storage this would be a cosmetic annoyance. For aged Burgundy with established sediment layers, the customer was right to call us promptly.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced compressor isolation mounts with OEM U-Line parts, re-torqued all mounting hardware, verified vibration level at the cabinet surface with a phone accelerometer before and after. Reduction from 0.8g peak to 0.1g — effectively vibration-free. Customer very relieved — the bottles had been in storage for 12 years and this was the first issue with the unit.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

