<!-- 10 FAQ -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">08 — Frequently Asked Questions</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Wine cooler repair — what people ask us</h2>

    <div class="faq-list">
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>How much does wine cooler repair cost in Los Angeles?</h3>
        <p>Our diagnostic fee is $89, applied toward the repair once you approve the work. Most wine cooler repairs run between $120 and $320. A thermostat, door seal, or fan motor replacement is toward the lower end. Compressor work or control board replacement on premium units like EuroCave, Sub-Zero, or Liebherr runs higher — we provide a written estimate before any work begins.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>My wine cooler isn't cooling — is it the compressor or something else?</h3>
        <p>It depends on the type of unit. On a thermoelectric unit, "not cooling" may not be a malfunction at all — these units can only cool about 20°F below ambient, so a warm room in LA summer can exceed their capacity. On a compressor-based unit, the condenser fan, thermostat, compressor, or refrigerant are the likely culprits. We diagnose the actual cause before recommending parts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What is the difference between thermoelectric and compressor wine coolers?</h3>
        <p>Thermoelectric coolers use a Peltier module — no moving parts, no vibration, very quiet, ideal for sediment-sensitive bottles. Their limitation: can only cool ~20°F below ambient. Compressor coolers work like a small refrigerator and can maintain wine storage temperature regardless of room temperature — more reliable in LA's warm climate. For serious collections in LA, compressor units are generally the better choice.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>My wine cooler has zones cooling differently — what's wrong?</h3>
        <p>Uneven cooling across zones usually points to a failed zone fan motor — each zone has its own fan. A thermostat or temperature sensor drifting in one zone, or a door seal gap, can also cause temperature variation. We test each zone independently before recommending parts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Does vibration from a wine cooler actually affect wine?</h3>
        <p>Yes, over time — particularly for aged wines with sediment. Vibration keeps sediment in suspension rather than allowing it to settle and can disrupt the slow processes involved in wine aging. A wine cooler that's suddenly much louder and vibrating more than usual is worth repairing promptly for a collection you're aging. Thermoelectric units are preferable for sediment-sensitive bottles precisely because they have no compressor vibration.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Do you repair EuroCave, Liebherr, and other European wine cooler brands?</h3>
        <p>Yes. EuroCave and Liebherr are the two European wine cooler brands we see most in LA's serious collector market. Parts for these units sometimes require ordering from specialized distributors — we're upfront about lead times when that applies. Sub-Zero, U-Line, and Vinotemp we stock parts for more readily.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What does the 90-day warranty cover on wine cooler repairs?</h3>
        <p>Every wine cooler repair we complete carries a 90-day warranty on both parts and labor. If the same issue returns within that window, we come back at no charge. That's in writing before we leave.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

